ul of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Hankford was born about 1350, in Buckland Brewer, Devon, England. He married Christina before 1380, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died on 12 December 1423, in Monkleigh, Devon, England, at the age of 74, and was buried in Monkleigh, Devon, England."},"et":{"About 1350–12 December 1423":"umbes 1350–12. detsember 1423","1335–1423":"1335–1423","1370–1419":"1370–1419","1379–1449":"1379–1449","–Female":"Surnud","1350–1423":"1350–1423","about 1370":"umbes 1370","before 1423":"enne 1423","27 April 1419":"27. aprill 1419","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","About 1350":"umbes 1350","1379":"1379","1423":"1423","1335":"1335","1399":"1399","12 December 1423":"12. detsember 1423","1419":"1419","before 1380":"enne 1380","1449":"1449","England":"England","Monkleigh, Devon, England":"Monkleigh, Devon, England","Clovelly, Devon, England":"Clovell